INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,1,'2011-09-06 13:51:38','2011-09-06 13:51:38','<a href=\"http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Tuition1.jpg\"><img src=\"http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Tuition1-300x94.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"SV_Header_Tuition\" width=\"300\" height=\"94\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-125\" /></a>Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','trash','open','open','','hello-world','','','2011-09-09 14:23:03','2011-09-09 14:23:03','',0,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2011-09-06 13:51:38','2011-09-06 13:51:38','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickies to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://localhost/studentvote/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','publish','open','open','','sample-page','','','2011-09-06 13:51:38','2011-09-06 13:51:38','',0,'http://localhost/studentvote/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(4,1,'2011-09-06 14:02:44','2011-09-06 14:02:44','','HOME','','publish','open','open','','home','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=4',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(5,1,'2011-09-06 14:02:44','2011-09-06 14:02:44','','HOW','','publish','open','open','','how','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=5',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(6,1,'2011-09-08 14:05:26','2011-09-08 14:05:26','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay about $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have slightly different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats will focus on making tuition more affordable and introducing measures to help with student debt.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','publish','open','open','','first-debate','','','2011-09-15 17:21:06','2011-09-15 17:21:06','',0,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=6',0,'post','',0),(230,2,'2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','','WHY','','publish','open','open','','why','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=230',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(231,2,'2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','','ORGANIZATION','','publish','open','open','','organization','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=231',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(115,1,'2011-09-08 19:09:30','2011-09-08 19:09:30','','monkey','','inherit','open','open','','monkey','','','2011-09-08 19:09:30','2011-09-08 19:09:30','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/monkey.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(7,1,'2011-09-06 14:05:37','2011-09-06 14:05:37','','First Debate','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision','','','2011-09-06 14:05:37','2011-09-06 14:05:37','',6,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=7',0,'revision','',0),(8,1,'2011-09-06 14:08:30','2011-09-06 14:08:30','','placeholder','','inherit','open','open','','placeholder','','','2011-09-06 14:08:30','2011-09-06 14:08:30','',1,'http://localhost/studentvote/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/placeholder1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(9,1,'2011-09-06 13:51:38','2011-09-06 13:51:38','Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision','','','2011-09-06 13:51:38','2011-09-06 13:51:38','',1,'http://localhost/studentvote/?p=9',0,'revision','',0),(10,2,'2011-09-08 19:33:16','2