e width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/J93x2a1NbWk?rel=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n[poll id=\"3\"]','First Debate - Vote','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-7','','','2011-09-08 18:47:13','2011-09-08 18:47:13','',50,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/120',0,'revision','',0),(121,2,'2011-09-08 18:47:07','2011-09-08 18:47:07','','First Debate - Comments','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-5','','','2011-09-08 18:47:07','2011-09-08 18:47:07','',48,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/121',0,'revision','',0),(122,2,'2011-09-08 19:15:51','2011-09-08 19:15:51','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/bXxAdgwFcWE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/SK6cYzOcxUg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nHello, my name is Bob Rae. \r\n\r\nIf you said to me, Mr. Rae, you\'ve got $5 billion dollars, how would you spend it? I\'m not sure I would be spending it all on absolutely free tuition. I have my doubts as to whether that\'s the wisest way to go. \r\n\r\nIt\'s a matter of saying, how much would that cost? The expense would be several billions of dollars shifting from the backs of students and parents and going to the government. Is that the best expenditure of that much money? Or should we be spending more money on providing student aid, student assistance, a better student loan program so that we\'re making sure everyone has got access to higher education.\r\n\r\nNot everyone goes to university. 55% or 60% of people don\'t go to college or university. They would tend to be lower income people, compared to those who do go to college and university. So the question would be: you\'re asking lower income people to pay a major subsidy to people who have higher incomes who are then going to be making higher incomes as a result of their going to college or university.\r\n\r\nStudents, 16, 17, 18, probably don\'t appreciate how much money they\'re going to be earning over the next 20, 30, 40, 50 years. It really isn\'t a barrier. It\'s only a barrier if we don\'t have the plans in place to help lower income students. Let\'s not forget there already is a huge public subsidy to go to college or university. When you pay your tuition of $5,500 or whatever it is, $6,000, when you pay that, you\'re not paying anywhere near the full cost of your education.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nHi, I’m John Ralston Saul.\r\n\r\nWhat you needed in 1900 was a grade 12 education, and what you need today is an undergraduate education. Most people didn\'t go to university, so the idea was by giving people a free grade 12 education, you opened up society to citizen participation and access to the workplace. Now that you need an undergraduate education to do the same thing, to a great extent, it\'s obvious that you should move the tuition free rule to the end of undergraduate education.\r\n\r\nYou know, I\'m sitting here in Germany, where undergraduate education is basically free, and nobody\'s ever said German education is of a lower level. You could just say, well let\'s just make undergraduate education free, and then all we have to do is set intellectual standards. Guess what? You\'ve just gotten rid of 80% of the bureaucracy. Instead of that, they want to run all of these programs, which are 19th century style semi-charity programs that say, \"Come see me, fill out this form. You need more documents, we\'re not sure. Maybe we can give you a scholarship, let\'s see which of the 4,000 scholarships you fit into. Oh, let\'s look over here, you don\'t fit into a scholarship, but maybe we could give you some charity.\"\r\n\r\nThink about all the time and money being wasted on that, when all you have to say is undergraduate education is free, getting in is going to be the problem because of intellectual standards. Anybody who does an analysis of the money going into universities knows that most of the money comes from the taxpayer anyways.\r\n\r\nSchools exist to create citizens. We live in a democracy. Democracies belong to citizens, not governments or corporations.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','First Debate - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','46-revision-8','','','2011-09-08 19:15:51','2011-09-08 19:15:51','',46,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/122',0,'revision','',0),(123,2,'2011-09-08 15:42:26','2011-09-08 15:42:26','<div style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;\">\r\n<div class=\"intro-text\">\r\nVestibulum ante ipsum primis in faucibus orci luctus et ultrices posuere cubilia Curae; Duis in dapibus turpis. Pellentesque porta pulvinar tristique. Suspendisse scelerisque adipiscing tellus, non euismod nunc tincidunt a. Proin tempus, erat varius mattis convallis, risus leo varius enim, in commodo tellus est a lectus. Sed hendrerit auctor tellus consequat venenatis. Curabitur at condimentum purus. Morbi adipiscing, mauris mollis dignissim ultricies, quam nisl dictum est, in semper sem justo vel diam. Sed adipiscing bibendum metus, condimentum imperdiet nisi accumsan a. Nunc cursus posuere cursus. Morbi rhoncus, quam quis dapibus mattis, sapien neque venenatis urna, vel malesuada metus felis at ligula. Aliquam erat volutpat. Sed elementum mauris facilisis turpis faucibus id rutrum elit fermentum.\r\n</div>\r\n<iframe src=\"http://www.coveritlive.com/index2.php/option=com_altcaster/task=viewaltcast/altcast_code=d01cd14c81/height=900/width=550\" scrolling=\"no\" height=\"900px\" width=\"550px\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\">&lt;a href=\"http://www.coveritlive.com/mobile.php/option=com_mobile/task=viewaltcast/altcast_code=d01cd14c81\" &gt;CoveritLive Demo&lt;/a&gt;</iframe>\r\n</div>\r\n','Events','','inherit','open','open','','80-revision-8','','','2011-09-08 15:42:26','2011-09-08 15:42:26','',80,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/123',0,'revision','',0),(126,2,'2011-09-08 17:22:16','2011-09-08 17:22:16','Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-3','','','2011-09-08 17:22:16','2011-09-08 17:22:16','',1,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/126',0,'revision','',0),(127,2,'2011-09-12 20:02:38','2011-09-12 20:02:38','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of its principle objectives is to get the province to stop depending on coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing this by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens who don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance – enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators. Another nine wind farms are set to become operational soon. But all of these wind farms only produce a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants that are headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWhile they are about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, wind turbines generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms saying that they\'re eyesores, that they kill local and migratory birds, and that they are often installed without consulting the citizens who are most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ¬– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas. But the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than those posed by wind turbines.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including establishing a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrats and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Wind Turbines','','publish','open','open','','should-ontario-invest-more-in-wind-energy','','','2011-09-22 13:14:47','2011-09-22 13:14:47','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/?p=127',0,'post','',0),(128,2,'2011-09-08 20:01:42','2011-09-08 20:01:42','','Should Ontario invest more in wind energy?','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision','','','2011-09-08 20:01:42','2011-09-08 20:01:42','',127,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/128',0,'revision','',0),(129,2,'2011-09-08 20:02:38','2011-09-08 20:02:38','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of the principle aspects of it is to get the province off of coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing so by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens that don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance, or enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators, while another nine are set to go operational soon. But that\'s only a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWind turbines, while about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms because they say they\'re eyesores, they kill local and migratory birds, and they were often installed without consulting the citizens who would be most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ­– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas, but the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than that of wind.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrat Party and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether or not they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Should Ontario invest more in wind energy?','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision-2','','','2011-09-08 20:02:38','2011-09-08 20:02:38','',127,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/129',0,'revision','',0),(130,2,'2011-09-08 19:08:12','2011-09-08 19:08:12','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay more than $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year. Complicating matters is the fact that more and more jobs require post-secondary degrees or diplomas, making the demand for a university or college education higher than ever.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats haven’t released their education platform yet, but they do note that tuition fees in Ontario became the highest under the Liberal government.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Should tuition be free in Ontario?','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-9','','','2011-09-08 19:08:12','2011-09-08 19:08:12','',6,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/130',0,'revision','',0),(131,2,'2011-09-08 20:02:58','2011-09-08 20:02:58','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of the principle aspects of it is to get the province off of coal 