ayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/NEW Debates/John Laforet.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/NEW Debates/JuttaNEW.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nI’m John Laforet, and I’m the president of Wind Concerns Ontario.\r\n\r\nI don’t believe the province should be investing more in wind energy, and the reason for that is it’s an expensive, unreliable, and often harmful form of energy production. The Liberals are allowing turbines to be dangerously close to homes, and they generate a lot of noise because they’re about 500 feet tall, they’ve got 8,000 moving parts, and the noise they’re generating makes it very hard for people to sleep in neighbouring homes. What that’s doing is it’s resulting in a whole host of negative health effects.\r\n\r\nOn the economics, wind energy costs four times what power otherwise costs in Ontario. We’re forced to buy it even when we don’t need it, which requires us to subsidize wind developers regardless of supply and demand. What that’s doing is that’s raising everyone’s electricity bills, and we’re wasting a lot of that energy by actually paying neighbouring jurisdictions to take it from us.\r\n\r\nWind power is generated when the wind feels like generating energy, not when we need it. So what that means is we have to build natural gas plants to back up that wind. Those natural gas plants run inefficiently because they’re turned on and off very frequently, depending on what the wind is doing. It’s a very unreasonable way to structure your economy, because it results in more pollution than if you just didn’t have the wind turbines operating.\r\n\r\nWind is still unreliable and will not solve our problems, it’s not going to replace coal because it is so unreliable, so what we need to do is look at solutions to how we’re going to generate clean, affordable, and reliable power.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nMy name is Jutta Splettstoesser, I’m the president of Friends of Wind Ontario.\r\n\r\nYou can see that all around the globe, wind generation is the fastest growing energy generation. I think that speaks for itself. We have to make a plan for the future. We want to go out of coal. By 2014, we want to shut down all the coal plants. What do we use as a substitute? What are our options? One of the options is to substitute it with wind.\r\n\r\nThese are future jobs. There’s many thousands of jobs created, and will be even more created through investment in wind turbines. We need people – qualified people – engineers, builders, electricians, that will have well-paid jobs in the future. For every megawatt of wind that’s produced, it’s about 2,000 liters of water that we preserve.\r\n\r\nThere are no direct health effects proven. There could be indirect health effects, and, just recently, this summer they had the Kent research tribunal, where it was said there could be indirect health effects, but nobody died from a turbine. We will improve technology over the years as well, and you can’t do that in a vacuum. You have to try different things out.\r\n\r\n If you look at the facts, all the benefits that are out there outweigh the complaints of a minority.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Wind Turbines - Debate','','publish','open','open','','wind-turbines-debate','','','2011-09-15 18:25:00','2011-09-15 18:25:00','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/?p=155',0,'post','',0),(156,2,'2011-09-09 15:32:55','2011-09-09 15:32:55','','Wind Turbines - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','155-revision','','','2011-09-09 15:32:55','2011-09-09 15:32:55','',155,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/156',0,'revision','',0),(157,2,'2011-09-15 14:30:09','2011-09-15 14:30:09','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n      <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/wIfR78OwPy8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n   <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/wIfR78OwPy8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\nI’m John Laforet, and I’m the president of Wind Concerns Ontario.\n\nI don’t believe the province should be investing more in wind energy, and the reason for that is it’s an expensive, unreliable, and often harmful form of energy production. The Liberals are allowing turbines to be dangerously close to homes, and they generate a lot of noise because they’re about 500 feet tall, they’ve got 8,000 moving parts, and the noise they’re generating makes it very hard for people to sleep in neighbouring homes. What that’s doing is it’s resulting in a whole host of negative health effects.\n\nOn the economics, wind energy costs four times what power otherwise costs in Ontario. We’re forced to buy it even when we don’t need it, which requires us to subsidize wind developers regardless of supply and demand. What that’s doing is that’s raising everyone’s electricity bills, and we’re wasting a lot of that energy by actually paying neighbouring jurisdictions to take it from us.\n\nWind power is generated when the wind feels like generating energy, not when we need it. So what that means is we have to build natural gas plants to back up that wind. Those natural gas plants run inefficiently because they’re turned on and off very frequently, depending on what the wind is doing. It’s a very unreasonable way to structure your economy, because it results in more pollution than if you just didn’t have the wind turbines operating.\n\nWind is still unreliable and will not solve our problems, it’s not going to replace coal because it is so unreliable, so what we need to do is look at solutions to how we’re going to generate clean, affordable, and reliable power.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\nMy name is Jutta Splettstoesser, I’m the president of Friends of Wind Ontario.\n\nYou can see that all around the globe, wind generation is the fastest growing energy generation. I think that speaks for itself. We have to make a plan for the future. We want to go out of coal. By 2014, we want to shut down all the coal plants. What do we use as a substitute? What are our options? One of the options is to substitute it with wind.\n\nThese are future jobs. There’s many thousands of jobs created, and will be even more created through investment in wind turbines. We need people – qualified people – engineers, builders, electricians, that will have well-paid jobs in the future. For every megawatt of wind that’s produced, it’s about 2,000 liters of water that we preserve.\n\nThere are no direct health effects proven. There could be indirect health effects, and, just recently, this summer they had the Kent research tribunal, where it was said there could be indirect health effects, but nobody died from a turbine. We will improve technology over the years as well, and you can’t do that in a vacuum. You have to try different things out.\n\n If you look at the facts, all the benefits that are out there outweigh the complaints of a minority.\n  </div>\n</div>','Wind Turbines - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','155-autosave','','','2011-09-15 14:30:09','2011-09-15 14:30:09','',155,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/157',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2011-09-07 21:02:16','2011-09-07 21:02:16','','Debates','','inherit','open','open','','26-revision-2','','','2011-09-07 21:02:16','2011-09-07 21:02:16','',26,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/144',0,'revision','',0),(145,1,'2011-09-08 17:41:23','2011-09-08 17:41:23','','Blog','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-3','','','2011-09-08 17:41:23','2011-09-08 17:41:23','',102,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/145',0,'revision','',0),(146,1,'2011-09-08 20:03:20','2011-09-08 20:03:20','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay more than $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year. Complicating matters is the fact that more and more jobs require post-secondary degrees or diplomas, making the demand for a university or college education higher than ever.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats haven’t released their education platform yet, but they do note that tuition fees in Ontario became the highest under the Liberal government.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-10','','','2011-09-08 20:03:20','2011-09-08 20:03:20','',6,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/146',0,'revision','',0),(147,1,'2011-09-08 19:33:36','2011-09-08 19:33:36','<a href=\"http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Tuition1.jpg\"><img src=\"http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Tuition1-300x94.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"SV_Header_Tuition\" width=\"300\" height=\"94\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-125\" /></a>Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-4','','','2011-09-08 19:33:36','2011-09-08 19:33:36','',1,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/147',0,'revision','',0),(148,1,'2011-09-09 14:22:51','2011-09-09 14:22:5