/><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/NEW Debates/Brian Day.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n[poll id=\"5\"]','Wait Times - Vote','','publish','open','open','','wait-times-vote','','','2011-09-15 16:39:17','2011-09-15 16:39:17','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/?p=178',0,'post','',0),(179,2,'2011-09-09 15:49:17','2011-09-09 15:49:17','','Wait Times - Vote','','inherit','open','open','','178-revision','','','2011-09-09 15:49:17','2011-09-09 15:49:17','',178,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/179',0,'revision','',0),(180,2,'2011-09-09 15:49:04','2011-09-09 15:49:04','','Wait Times - Comment','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-3','','','2011-09-09 15:49:04','2011-09-09 15:49:04','',175,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/180',0,'revision','',0),(181,2,'2011-09-09 15:48:42','2011-09-09 15:48:42','','Wait Times - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','173-revision-2','','','2011-09-09 15:48:42','2011-09-09 15:48:42','',173,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/181',0,'revision','',0),(182,2,'2011-09-09 15:48:18','2011-09-09 15:48:18','','Wait Times - Question','','inherit','open','open','','171-revision-2','','','2011-09-09 15:48:18','2011-09-09 15:48:18','',171,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/182',0,'revision','',0),(183,2,'2011-09-09 15:47:29','2011-09-09 15:47:29','Essay coming soon.','Wait Times','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-2','','','2011-09-09 15:47:29','2011-09-09 15:47:29','',169,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/183',0,'revision','',0),(184,2,'2011-09-09 15:51:52','2011-09-09 15:51:52','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"3\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/H6LCdmA7fO4\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n   <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/ZQFPH8AA3Z8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\nHello, my name is Bob Rae. \n\nIf you said to me, Mr. Rae, you\'ve got $5 billion dollars, how would you spend it? I\'m not sure I would be spending it all on absolutely free tuition. I have my doubts as to whether that\'s the wisest way to go. \n\nIt\'s a matter of saying, how much would that cost? The expense would be several billions of dollars shifting from the backs of students and parents and going to the government. Is that the best expenditure of that much money? Or should we be spending more money on providing student aid, student assistance, a better student loan program so that we\'re making sure everyone has got access to higher education.\n\nNot everyone goes to university. 55% or 60% of people don\'t go to college or university. They would tend to be lower income people, compared to those who do go to college and university. So the question would be: you\'re asking lower income people to pay a major subsidy to people who have higher incomes who are then going to be making higher incomes as a result of their going to college or university.\n\nStudents, 16, 17, 18, probably don\'t appreciate how much money they\'re going to be earning over the next 20, 30, 40, 50 years. It really isn\'t a barrier. It\'s only a barrier if we don\'t have the plans in place to help lower income students. Let\'s not forget there already is a huge public subsidy to go to college or university. When you pay your tuition of $5,500 or whatever it is, $6,000, when you pay that, you\'re not paying anywhere near the full cost of your education.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\nHi, I’m John Ralston Saul.\n\nWhat you needed in 1900 was a grade 12 education, and what you need today is an undergraduate education. Most people didn\'t go to university, so the idea was by giving people a free grade 12 education, you opened up society to citizen participation and access to the workplace. Now that you need an undergraduate education to do the same thing, to a great extent, it\'s obvious that you should move the tuition free rule to the end of undergraduate education.\n\nYou know, I\'m sitting here in Germany, where undergraduate education is basically free, and nobody\'s ever said German education is of a lower level. You could just say, well let\'s just make undergraduate education free, and then all we have to do is set intellectual standards. Guess what? You\'ve just gotten rid of 80% of the bureaucracy. Instead of that, they want to run all of these programs, which are 19th century style semi-charity programs that say, \"Come see me, fill out this form. You need more documents, we\'re not sure. Maybe we can give you a scholarship, let\'s see which of the 4,000 scholarships you fit into. Oh, let\'s look over here, you don\'t fit into a scholarship, but maybe we could give you some charity.\"\n\nThink about all the time and money being wasted on that, when all you have to say is undergraduate education is free, getting in is going to be the problem because of intellectual standards. Anybody who does an analysis of the money going into universities knows that most of the money comes from the taxpayer anyways.\n\nSchools exist to create citizens. We live in a democracy. Democracies belong to citizens, not governments or corporations.\n  </div>\n</div>','Wait Times - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','173-autosave','','','2011-09-09 15:51:52','2011-09-09 15:51:52','',173,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/184',0,'revision','',0),(185,2,'2011-09-09 15:49:46','2011-09-09 15:49:46','','Wait Times - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','173-revision-3','','','2011-09