lly free, and nobody\'s ever said German education is of a lower level. You could just say, well let\'s just make undergraduate education free, and then all we have to do is set intellectual standards. Guess what? You\'ve just gotten rid of 80% of the bureaucracy. Instead of that, they want to run all of these programs, which are 19th century style semi-charity programs that say, \"Come see me, fill out this form. You need more documents, we\'re not sure. Maybe we can give you a scholarship, let\'s see which of the 4,000 scholarships you fit into. Oh, let\'s look over here, you don\'t fit into a scholarship, but maybe we could give you some charity.\"\r\n\r\nThink about all the time and money being wasted on that, when all you have to say is undergraduate education is free, getting in is going to be the problem because of intellectual standards. Anybody who does an analysis of the money going into universities knows that most of the money comes from the taxpayer anyways.\r\n\r\nSchools exist to create citizens. We live in a democracy. Democracies belong to citizens, not governments or corporations.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Wind Turbines - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','155-revision-5','','','2011-09-09 15:39:16','2011-09-09 15:39:16','',155,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/192',0,'revision','',0),(195,2,'2011-09-09 18:04:37','2011-09-09 18:04:37','','Leaf','','inherit','open','open','','leaf','','','2011-09-09 18:04:37','2011-09-09 18:04:37','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Leaf.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(196,2,'2011-09-09 18:05:41','2011-09-09 18:05:41','','Ballot','','inherit','open','open','','ballot','','','2011-09-09 18:05:41','2011-09-09 18:05:41','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Ballot.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(197,2,'2011-09-09 18:06:25','2011-09-09 18:06:25','','Microphone','','inherit','open','open','','microphone','','','2011-09-09 18:06:25','2011-09-09 18:06:25','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Microphone.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(209,2,'2011-09-09 19:07:49','2011-09-09 19:07:49','','Trophy','','inherit','open','open','','trophy','','','2011-09-09 19:07:49','2011-09-09 19:07:49','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Trophy.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(202,2,'2011-09-09 18:24:55','2011-09-09 18:24:55','','Crowd','','inherit','open','open','','crowd','','','2011-09-09 18:24:55','2011-09-09 18:24:55','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Crowd.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(203,2,'2011-09-09 18:41:19','2011-09-09 18:41:19','','Ballot','','inherit','open','open','','ballot-2','','','2011-09-09 18:41:19','2011-09-09 18:41:19','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Ballot1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(207,2,'2011-09-09 19:05:30','2011-09-09 19:05:30','','Laptop','','inherit','open','open','','laptop','','','2011-09-09 19:05:30','2011-09-09 19:05:30','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Laptop.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(211,2,'2011-09-09 19:11:00','2011-09-09 19:11:00','','Ballot','','inherit','open','open','','ballot-3','','','2011-09-09 19:11:00','2011-09-09 19:11:00','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Ballot2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(212,2,'2011-09-08 20:04:12','2011-09-08 20:04:12','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of the principle aspects of it is to get the province off of coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing so by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens that don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance, or enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators, while another nine are set to go operational soon. But that\'s only a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWind turbines, while about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms because they say they\'re eyesores, they kill local and migratory birds, and they were often installed without consulting the citizens who would be most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ­– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas, but the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than that of wind.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrat Party and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether or not they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Wind Turbines','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision-4','','','2011-09-08 20:04:12','2011-09-08 20:04:12','',127,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/212',0,'revision','',0),(213,2,'2011-09-09 15:50:19','2011-09-09 15:50:19','Essay coming soon.','Wait Times','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-3','','','2011-09-09 15:50:19','2011-09-09 15:50:19','',169,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/213',0,'revision','',0),(214,1,'2011-09-08 16:20:09','2011-09-08 16:20:09','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"510\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/9KBZwVF1kFA?rel=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','What\'s the most important issue facing Ontario?','','inherit','open','open','','36-revision-6','','','2011-09-08 16:20:09','2011-09-08 16:20:09','',36,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/214',0,'revision','',0),(585,2,'2011-09-18 22:05:02','2011-09-18 22:05:02','General crime rates might be dropping across the country, but make no mistake about it: hate crimes – in which a suspect attacks somebody because of their race, faith, sexual orientation, gender, or otherwise – are on the rise. Many cities in Ontario, from major urban centres like Toronto, Ottawa, and London, to smaller communities such as Peterborough and Guelph, all reported more hate crime incidents in 2010 than in the years before. Part of the rise is due to more people reporting hate crimes to police in the first place, but crimes against specific minorities also tend to increase when the economy dips.\r\n\r\nOntario, of course, is one of the most diverse jurisdictions on the planet, with people from just about every country and religion on the planet settling here, which makes the need to confront hate crimes all the more pressing. And while hate crimes are still relatively few and far between, their impact on communities – whether it\'s swastikas painted on a synagogue, or a man getting beaten up just because he\'s gay – is often far greater than typical offences.\r\n\r\nDespite their prevalence in Ontario, none of the three major political parties have any specific plans for tackling the rising number of hate crimes in the province. Regardless, authorities on the subject say the key getting rid of hate crimes is to educate the population about the various differences among Ontario\'s many minority groups. Others suggest harsher punishments for those convicted of hate crimes, so as to send a message of deterrence to anyone else who might consider committing one. Another train of thought says hate crimes should be treated the same as any other crime, so as to not glorify the motives of people committing them. Needless to say, there isn\'t a single correct answer on how to combat hate crimes, but it\'s an issue that still needs confronting.','Hate Crimes / Cyber Bullying','','trash','open','open','','hate-crimes-cyber-bullying','','','2011-09-19 15:55:20','2011-09-19 15:55:20','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=585',0,'post','',0),(216,2,'2011-09-09 21:03:48','2011-09-09 21:03:48','<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+Communist/Communist+-+Farms.flv\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/k1LeM.jpg\">\r\n  Communist Party of Canada (Ontario)\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+Green+Party/LEADERS+-+Mike+Schreiner+answers+Indigo+Christ.flv\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/3GgnJ.jpg\">\r\n  Green Party of Ontario\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEWNEWLIBERAL+RESPONSES/Liberal+Response+5.flv\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/2jqKw.jpg\">\r\n  Ontario Liberal Party\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"leader-answer\">\r\n<img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Nvv0P.jpg\">\r\nOntario New Democratic Party (Coming soon!)\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/Hudak+FLVs/Indigo+-+Famers+.wmv.flv\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/vnrri.jpg\">\r\n  Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario\r\n</div><div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/Special+Needs+Responses/PPSN+-+Farming.mp4\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/t7IAN.jpg\">\r\n  The Party for People with Special Needs\r\n</div>','Leader Answers - Farming','','publish','open','open','','whats-22-answers','','','2011-09-20 17:22:49','2011-09-20 17:22:49','',0,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/?p=216',0,'post','',0),(217,2,'2011-09-09 21:03:44