 a university or college education higher than ever.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats haven’t released their education platform yet, but they do note that tuition fees in Ontario became the highest under the Liberal government.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-11','','','2011-09-09 14:22:34','2011-09-09 14:22:34','',6,'http://sv.staging.verto.ca/uncategorized/224',0,'revision','',0),(225,2,'2011-09-12 19:43:11','2011-09-12 19:43:11','Tell us using words, a photograph, or a video using the form on this page. The entry that gets the most votes by the Ontario election October 6 will win the opportunity to meet the next Ontario Premier. This 