o make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats will focus on making tuition more affordable and introducing measures to help with student debt.\n\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition just be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-autosave','','','2011-09-11 14:43:15','2011-09-11 14:43:15','',6,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/228',0,'revision','',0),(229,2,'2011-09-10 00:23:45','2011-09-10 00:23:45','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay more than $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year. Complicating matters is the fact that more and more jobs require post-secondary degrees or diplomas, making the demand for a university or college education higher than ever.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats haven’t released their education platform yet, but they do note that tuition fees in Ontario became the highest under the Liberal government.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-12','','','2011-09-10 00:23:45','2011-09-10 00:23:45','',6,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/229',0,'revision','',0),(232,2,'2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','','PROJECTS','','publish','open','open','','projects','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=232',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(233,2,'2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','','REGISTER','','publish','open','open','','register','','','2011-09-11 15:11:54','2011-09-11 15:11:54','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=233',6,'nav_menu_item','',0),(234,2,'2011-09-11 15:11:55','2011-09-11 15:11:55','','CONTACT','','publish','open','open','','contact','','','2011-09-11 15:11:55','2011-09-11 15:11:55','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=234',7,'nav_menu_item','',0),(235,2,'2011-09-23 11:13:34','2011-09-23 11:13:34','One in four students in Canada is considered overweight, and that number is expected to rise in the coming years. Unbalanced diets and inactive lifestyles are a big part of the reason Canada\'s getting fat, and they pose long-term threats to Ontario\'s health-care system. Overweight and obese people are more likely to develop heart disease, diabetes, depression, and a raft of other issues than those with healthier body weights. As if a rapidly aging population wasn\'t straining the health-care system enough, the looming obesity crisis only stands to complicate matters.\r\n\r\nFinding a way to curb the growth of Ontarians\' waistlines is a tricky proposition. The government can\'t simply tell people what they should and shouldn\'t eat. However, there are ways to encourage citizens to lead healthier lifestyles. One proposal is that all students should be required to take gym classes throughout their entire school career, as getting young people to develop healthy habits such as exercising is seen as one of the best ways to help them ward off obesity for the rest of their lives. Other suggestions include posting the calorie counts of meals on restaurant menus, banning junk food in schools, and making healthier foods – especially fruits and vegetables – more affordable for more people.\r\n\r\nSo far in this election, the New Democratic Party has proposed introducing mandatory gym class, forcing chain restaurants to display their food’s nutritional information, and banning junk-food advertisements aimed at kids. The Liberals want to launch a “Council on Childhood Obesity” that would aim to bring obesity levels in children down by 20 per cent, while the Progressive Conservatives haven\'t touched the issue yet. What do you think: Would measures like mandatory gym class help the province get in shape?','Obesity / Health','','publish','open','open','','obesity-health','','','2011-09-23 20:11:25','2011-09-23 20:11:25','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=235',0,'post','',0),(236,2,'2011-09-11 15:13:58','2011-09-11 15:13:58','','Obesity / Health','','inherit','open','open','','235-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:13:58','2011-09-11 15:13:58','',235,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/236',0,'revision','',0),(237,2,'2011-09-22 12:14:18','2011-09-22 12:14:18','Fifteen per cent of youth between the ages of 15 and 25 in Ontario are unemployed. This number is twice as high as the unemployment rate for the province as a whole, and has grown considerably since the recession of 2008-09. Making matters worse is the rising price of tuition for college and university programs, as many students must take on staggering levels of debt to pay for their education without a steady income to help them out. And many of the jobs that youth do end up in are in low-skill, low-wage fields such as hospitality or retail. Imagine you\'re well into your 20s: You have a degree or a diploma, but, as a result of the high costs of education, you are tens of thousands of dollars in debt, and you can\'t find a job that puts your skills to use. In this scenario, it\'s easy to become dispirited.\r\n\r\nBut youth unemployment, or underemployment, doesn\'t just affect those without jobs. If university graduates can\'t find jobs, there\'s a good chance they\'ll end up living at home, putting additional financial strain on their parents. Furthermore, the economy is missing out on the one time of people’s lives when they can fully devote themselves to their careers before having to worry about family, home ownership, or other such changes that come about later in life. And letting the career-specific skills youth develop in college or university go to waste as they work menial jobs means they might never live up to their full potential.\r\n\r\nCreating jobs is a hot topic in this election. The Progressive Conservatives want to create 200,000 new apprenticeship positions over the next four years, while the New Democratic Party says it will offer tax credits to any employer that creates a new full-time position. The Liberals have announced a similar measure to get employers to hire immigrants, and are running on their record of restoring more jobs to the province than were lost during the recession. While creating jobs has been one of the most dominant themes of the election campaign so far, the three main political parties don\'t offer a whole lot in the way of addressing youth unemployment specifically. What role should the government play in getting the youth-unemployment rate down, and what\'s the best way to do so?','Youth Employment','','publish','open','open','','youth-employment','','','2011-09-23 20:11:54','2011-09-23 20:11:54','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=237',0,'post','',0),(238,2,'2011-09-11 15:14:37','2011-09-11 15:14:37','','Youth Employment','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:14:37','2011-09-11 15:14:37','',237,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/238',0,'revision','',0),(239,2,'2011-10-01 15:14:51','2011-10-01 15:14:51','Coming soon.','Taxes on Individuals','','future','open','open','','taxes-on-individuals','','','2011-09-13 21:12:57','2011-09-13 21:12:57','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=239',0,'post','',0),(240,2,'2011-09-11 15:14:59','2011-09-11 15:14:59','','Taxes on Individuals','','inherit','open','open','','239-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:14:59','2011-09-11 15:14:59','',239,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/240',0,'revision','',0),(241,2,'2011-09-11 15:15:06','2011-09-11 15:15:06','','Taxes on Individuals','','inherit','open','open','','239-revision-2','','','2011-09-11 15:15:06','2011-09-11 15:15:06','',239,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/241',0,'revision','',0),(242,2,'2011-09-18 15:15:21','2011-09-18 15:15:21','The introduction of the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) was among the biggest policy changes that the McGuinty government made. The HST combined the Provincial Sales Tax (PST) and the federal Goods and Services Tax (GST) into one “harmonized” tax of 13 per cent. The HST is meant to streamline the country\'s taxation systems: It rolls the various provincial sales taxes into a common tax that has now been implemented in five provinces. The more efficient the tax system, say some economists, the easier it is for businesses to pass on savings to consumers. But the HST has also added taxes that weren\'t there before, such as on gasoline, electricity, heating, lawyers\' fees, internet subscriptions, and jobs performed by plumbers and electricians.\r\n\r\nWhile there has been a fair bit of criticism in Ontario over the new tax, the reaction here has been nothing compared to that in British Columbia, where former premier Bill Vander Zalm led a petition against the tax, resulting in a vote in which the citizens of B.C. decided to do away with the HST.\r\n\r\nThe HST has been in effect in Ontario since July of 2010. To help families cope with the transition to the new taxation system, the government sent out rebates intended to cover some of the new costs associated with the HST.\r\n\r\nAll three of Ontario\'s major political parties agree that we should keep the HST, but they have different opinions on just what should be affected by the tax. The Liberals stand by their decision to introduce the HST in the first place, and are content with the things that it currently affects. The Progressive Conservatives want to remove the HST from home heating and hydro, and the NDP wants it taken off of gas in addition to heating and hydro. In general, the parties seem to be OK with the tax, then. How about you?','HST','','publish','open','open','','hst','','','2011-09-20 00:54:03','2011-09-20 00:54:03','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=242',0,'post','',0),(243,2,'2011-09-11 15:15:28','2011-09-11 15:15:28','','HST','','inherit','open','open','','242-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:15:28','2011-09-11 15:15:28','',242,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/243',0,'revision','',0),(244,2,'2011-09-21 15:15:41','2011-09-21 15:15:41','Whether it’s gridlock in Toronto, public transit in Ottawa, or the quality of roads in the North, transportation is an issue that affects each and every person in Ontario. And with the province\'s population growing every day, its transit needs aren\'t about to get any easier in the coming years. Toronto, for example, has the longest commute times of anywhere in the country, and the worst gridlock (or traffic jams) in the continent. Finding ways to ease congestion will not only make the region more livable, but will also help the country\'s economic heartland continue to grow well into this century. Public transit certainly plays a part in that future, but just who pays for it – users, the city, the province, the federal government, or a mixture of all of them – is still up for debate.\r\n\r\nIn northern Ontario, there are billions of dollars in minerals just waiting to be mined, but there aren\'t enough roads to get those minerals out of there. Developing proper infrastructure in the more remote parts of the province could help us tap their economic potential for the benefit of the entire province. Unfortunately, saying something and actually making it happen are two very different matters, and, more often than not, when it comes to plans for development, the sparsely populated North gets overlooked in favour of vote-rich southern Ontario.\r\n\r\nEach of the three major political parties has a different plan on how to cope with transit issues, but they all tend to focus on the Greater Toronto Area, or GTA. The New Democratic Party, for example, promises to share the cost of public transportation with cities in exchange for a freeze on transit fares that would prevent them from changing for four years. The Progressive Conservatives are pledging $35 billion to improve infrastructure such as roads, highways, and public-transit lines, and the cornerstone of the Liberals\' transit promises is a plan to expand full-day GO Train service around the GTA.\r\n\r\nFrom traffic jams to a lack of sufficient roads, urban and rural areas each face their own dilemmas when it comes to issues of transportation. Thus, in terms of government policy and funding for transportation, there is much debate over which concerns to address first. Given what you know, where do you think our priorities should lie?','Transportation','','publish','open','open','','transit-city','','','2011-09-22 13:34:11','2011-09-22 13:34:11','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=244',0,'post','',0),(245,2,'2011-09-11 15:15:47','2011-09-11 15:15:47','','Transit City','','inherit','open','open','','244-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:15:47','2011-09-11 15:15:47','',244,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/245',0,'revision','',0),(246,2,'2011-10-01 15:15:56','2011-10-01 15:15:56','Coming soon.','Greenhouse Gases','','future','open','open','','greenhouse-gases','','','2011-09-13 21:13:15','2011-09-13 21:13:15','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=246',0,'post','',0),(247,2,'2011-09-11 15:16:01','2011-09-11 15:16:01','','Greenhouse Gases','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:16:01','2011-09-11 15:16:01','',246,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/247',0,'revision','',0),(248,2,'2011-09-19 15:16:11','2011-09-19 15:16:11','General crime rates might be dropping across the country, but make no mistake: Hate crimes – in which a person attacks someone else because of his or her race, faith, sexual orientation, gender, or other characteristics – are on the rise. Many cities in Ontario (from major urban centres like Toronto, Ottawa, and London, to smaller communities such as Peterborough and Guelph) reported more hate crimes in 2010 than in the years before. Part of this increase is due to the fact that more people are reporting hate crimes to police than they used to (especially now that more people are aware of what hate crimes are, and how serious they are), but crimes against specific minorities also tend to increase when the economy dips.\r\n\r\nOntario is one of the most diverse regions in the world, with people from just about every country and religion settling here. This makes the need to confront hate crimes in this province all the more pressing. And while hate crimes are still relatively few and far between, their impact on communities – whether it\'s swastikas painted on a synagogue, or a man getting beaten up just because he\'s gay – is often far greater than the impact of typical offences. When hate crimes are committed, the victims (and the religious, gender, ethnic, or other groups that they represent) are made to feel unwelcome, and often live in fear of being targeted for future crimes.\r\n\r\nDespite the rising number of hate crimes in Ontario, none of the three major political parties have any specific plans for tackling the problem. Regardless, some authorities on the subject say the key to getting rid of hate crimes is to educate the population about the differences among Ontario\'s many minority groups, so that those differences are no longer seen as “other.” On the other hand, some people suggest there should be harsher punishments for those convicted of hate crimes, since this could discourage others from committing similar crimes. There is much debate over the best way to address this serious issue, but the evidence is clear: Something must be done. Given what you’ve learned, what do you think is the best way to combat hate crimes in Ontario?','Hate Crimes','','publish','open','open','','hate-crimes','','','2011-09-23 02:10:14','2011-09-23 02:10:14','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=248',0,'post','',0),(249,2,'2011-09-11 15:16:18','2011-09-11 15:16:18','','Hate Crimes','','inherit','open','open','','248-revision','','','2011-09-11 15:16:18','2011-09-11 15:16:18','',248,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/249',0,'revision','',0),(250,2,'2011-09-11 15:16:23','2011-09-11 15:16:23','','Hate Crimes','','inherit','open','open','','248-revision-2','','','2011-09-11 15:16:23','2011-09-11 15:16:23','',248,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/250',0,'revision','',0),(251,2,'2011-09-09 20:57:06','2011-09-09 20:57:06','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"510\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/9KBZwVF1kFA?rel=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfulls