,'open','','48-revision-6','','','2011-09-08 19:17:57','2011-09-08 19:17:57','',48,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/354',0,'revision','',0),(355,2,'2011-09-09 21:14:29','2011-09-09 21:14:29','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/PlSDXsvt7Wc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/ZQFPH8AA3Z8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n[poll id=\"6\"]','Wind Turbines - Vote','','inherit','open','open','','163-revision-6','','','2011-09-09 21:14:29','2011-09-09 21:14:29','',163,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/355',0,'revision','',0),(356,2,'2011-09-09 15:49:33','2011-09-09 15:49:33','','Wait Times - Comment','','inherit','open','open','','175-revision-4','','','2011-09-09 15:49:33','2011-09-09 15:49:33','',175,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/356',0,'revision','',0),(357,2,'2011-09-09 16:24:46','2011-09-09 16:24:46','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/H6LCdmA7fO4\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/_7UvZ9x7QDk\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nI’m Deb Matthews. I’m the Minister of Health and Long-Term Care for Ontario.\r\n\r\nWe really believe in Ontario, we believe in Canada that everyone should have universal access and that means everyone should get the care they need because they need care, not because they can afford to pay for it. So for Canadians, this is kind of what makes us different than other places in the world, and I think that Canadians really value their universal health care system.\r\n\r\nIf we introduce a private component, what that means is that people with the money to pay will get care faster. It will be a shorter wait time for them, but it will be a longer wait time for everyone else. And we really do believe in equal access to care, we really do believe that we should have the best possible care for everyone, not just those who can afford to pay for it.\r\n\r\nI think we’ve come a long way in the last eight years, we’re providing much better care, more people have a family doctor now then before, our wait times are half of what they used to be. So for me, the issue is: let’s invest in our health care system so all of us get excellent care.\r\n\r\nWe only have a certain number of doctors, we only have a certain number of nurses, and if we’re pulling doctors from our publicly funded system to work in private health care, we are, by definition, reducing the resources in our public system.\r\n\r\nWhen the wait times were so long, people really were arguing for two-tier health care. We’ve come a long way in brining those wait times down. In fact, we’ve now got the shortest wait times in all of Canada, we’re meeting our targets on almost all of our surgical wait times. We now measure our wait times, we publicly report. People can go online, and see what wait times are for all the different procedures at all the different hospitals. We really track it so that we can make investments to keep those wait times down, or to get them down even lower if they’re still too high. So for me, it’s about putting the resources in the system that the system requires.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nMy name is Brian Day, I’m an orthopedic surgeon, I’m the medical director of Cambie Surgery Centre, and I’m a former President of the Canadian Medical Association. \r\n\r\nThe group in Canada that has the least access to health services and has the poorest health outcomes, are the poor. In France, in Belgium, in Switzerland, in Germany, in Austria, the rich and poor alike have rapid access to necessary health care, that the poor and underprivileged in Canada do not have. So, there are systems out there that work better than ours, that have universal health care, everyone’s covered, and they outperform us in every way.\r\n\r\nAt a big hospital in Toronto, or Vancouver, or Montreal, a patient goes to a hospital. That hospital is funded by a fixed global budget per year, say it’s a billion dollars, every patient that goes to that hospital uses up some of the money. So a patient going to a hospital is looked upon as an expense. Money should follow the patients, so a hospital that does not treat patients in an efficient and have good performance, good outcomes, is actually penalized by receiving little revenue compared to one that is efficient.\r\n\r\nMost nursing graduates in Alberta cannot get a full-time job. Many of them leave because they can’t get a full-time job. So to start saying we’ll lose manpower – we’re losing manpower now because we’re not opening our hospitals. We’re closing them at three and four o’clock in the afternoon, despite the fact that we have probably across the country over a million people waiting to get into health care. And these patients get worse while they wait.\r\n\r\nWhat we’re talking about here is a monopoly. Do you believe in a single government monopoly for any service? I don’t think monopolies serve consumers well.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Wait Times - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','173-revision-5','','','2011-09-09 16:24:46','2011-09-09 16:24:46','',173,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/357',0,'revision','',0),(358,2,'2011-09-09 19:27:42','2011-09-09 19:27:42','Health care is always one of the top issues in any provincial election, and with an aging population and budgets that need balancing, it\'s as pressing an issue as it\'s ever been. One of the key markers of how well our health-care system is run is how long wait times are for emergency-room visits and surgeries. By this measure, Ontario is ahead of the rest of the country. However, wait times vary substantially from region to region within Ontario. This is because wait times largely depend on the number of hospitals, doctors, and other patients needing treatment nearby. There\'s always room for improvement, but how to go about making improvements is often a controversial topic, especially in a country that puts its public health-care system alongside hockey and peace, order, and good government in a list of things that matter most to us.\r\n\r\nThat\'s partly why it\'s so difficult – for politicians, at least – to bring up the idea of establishing more private (as in, for-profit) services as a way to combat wait times. Private health care gives the impression that those who can afford it have an unfair advantage over those who can’t. There is also a sense that it would undermine the public system by stealing resources and doctors. On the other hand, many European countries have a mixture of private and public health care, and access to surgeries and emergency rooms in those countries is substantially better than here in Ontario. Indeed, many in the health-care community blame the monopoly that provincial governments have on health delivery for the inefficiencies that plague the system.\r\n\r\nNone of the three major political parties have brought up private services as a remedy for wait times. The Liberals are running on their record, over the past eight years, of opening hospitals, creating jobs for thousands of nurses, and getting wait times down to the lowest in the country. The New Democratic Party promises to cut wait times in half, while the Progressive Conservatives say they will establish wait-time guarantees that hospital CEOs will be responsible for meeting. The merits of each of these proposals aside, should the province start considering more private delivery of services to help reduce wait times?\r\n','Wait Times','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-4','','','2011-09-09 19:27:42','2011-09-09 19:27:42','',169,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/358',0,'revision','',0),(359,2,'2011-09-13 15:44:00','2011-09-13 15:44:00','Health care is always one of the top issues in any provincial election, and with an aging population and budgets that need balancing, it\'s as pressing an issue as it\'s ever been. One of the key markers of how well our health-care system is run is how long wait times are for emergency-room visits and surgeries. By this measure, Ontario is ahead of the rest of the country. However, wait times vary substantially from region to region within Ontario. This is because wait times largely depend on the number of hospitals, doctors, and other patients needing treatment nearby. There\'s always room for improvement, but how to go about making improvements is often a controversial topic, especially in a country that puts its public health-care system alongside hockey and peace, order, and good government in a list of things that matter most to us.\r\n\r\nThat\'s partly why it\'s so difficult – for politicians, at least – to bring up the idea of establishing more private (as in, for-profit) services as a way to combat wait times. Private health care gives the impression that those who can afford it have an unfair advantage over those who can’t. There is also a sense that it would undermine the public system by stealing resources and doctors. On the other hand, many European countries have a mixture of private and public health care, and access to surgeries and emergency rooms in those countries is substantially better than here in Ontario. Indeed, many in the health-care community blame the monopoly that provincial governments have on health delivery for the inefficiencies that plague the system.\r\n\r\nNone of the three major political parties have brought up private services as a remedy for wait times. The Liberals are running on their record, over the past eight years, of opening hospitals, creating jobs for thousands of nurses, and getting wait times down to the lowest in the country. The New Democratic Party promises to cut wait times in half, while the Progressive Conservatives say they will establish wait-time guarantees that hospital CEOs will be responsible for meeting. The merits of each of these proposals aside, should the province start considering more private delivery of services to help reduce wait times?\r\n','Wait Times','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-5','','','2011-09-13 15:44:00','2011-09-13 15:44:00','',169,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/359',0,'revision','',0),(360,2,'2011-09-12 15:01:07','2011-09-12 15:01:07','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"420\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/UJfh0VrQmRA\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Wait Times - Question','','inherit','open','open','','171-revision-4','','','2011-09-12 15:01:07','2011-09-12 15:01:07','',171,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/360',0,'revision','',0),(361,2,'2011-09-13 15:24:28','2011-09-13 15:24:28','<script>\r\nvar idcomments_acct = \'066bba3582108cb66ff7a183c5e6a3b0\';\r\nvar idcomments_post_id;\r\nvar idcomments_post_url;\r\n</script>\r\n<span id=\"IDCommentsPostTitle\" style=\"display:none\"></span>\r\n<script type=\'text/javascript\' src=\'http://www.intensedebate.com/js/genericCommentWrapperV2.js\'></script>','Tuition - Comments','','inherit','open','open','','48-revision-7','','','2011-09-13 15:24:28','2011-09-13 15:24:28','',48,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/361',0,'revision','',0),(362,2,'2011-09-08 19:18:15','2011-09-08 19:18:15','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/bXxAdgwFcWE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/SK6cYzOcxUg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nHello, my name is Bob Rae. \r\n\r\nIf you said to me, Mr. Rae, you\'ve got $5 billion dollars, how would you spend it? I\'m not sure I would be spending it all on absolutely free tuition. I have my doubts as to whether that\'s the wisest way to go. \r\n\r\nIt\'s a matter of saying, how much would that cost? The expense would be several billions of dollars shifting from the backs of students and parents and going to the government. Is that the best expenditure of that much money? Or should we be spending more money on providing student aid, student assistance, a better student loan program so that we\'re making sure everyone has got access to higher education.\r\n\r\nNot everyone goes to university. 55% or 60% of people don\'t go to college or university. They would tend to be lower income people, compared to those who do go to college and university. So the question would be: you\'re asking lower income people to pay a major subsidy to people who have higher incomes who are then going to be making higher incomes as a result of their going to college or university.\r\n\r\nStudents, 16, 17, 18, probably don\'t appreciate how much money they\'re going to be earning over the next 20, 30, 40, 50 years. It really isn\'t a barrier. It\'s only a barrier if we don\'t have the plans in place to help lower income students. Let\'s not forget there already is a huge public subsidy to go to college or university. When you pay your tuition of $5,500 or whatever it is, $6,000, when you pay that, you\'re not paying anywhere near the full cost of your education.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nHi, I’m John Ralston Saul.\r\n\r\nWhat you needed in 1900 was a grade 12 education, and what you need today is an undergraduate education. Most people didn\'t go to university, so the idea was by giving people a free grade 12 education, you opened up society to citizen participation and access to the workplace. Now that you need an undergraduate education to do the same thing, to a great extent, it\'s obvious that you should move the tuition free rule to the end of undergraduate education.\r\n\r\nYou know, I\'m sitting here in Germany, where undergraduate education is basically free, and nobody\'s ever said German education is of a lower level. You could just say, well let\'s just make undergraduate education free, and then all we have to do is set intellectual standards. Guess what? You\'ve just gotten rid of 80% of the bureaucracy. Instead of that, they want to run all of these programs, which are 19th century style semi-charity programs that say, \"Come see me, fill out this form. You need more documents, we\'re not sure. Maybe we can give you a scholarship, let\'s see which of the 4,000 scholarships you fit into. Oh, let\'s look over here, you don\'t fit into a scholarship, but maybe we could give you some charity.\"\r\n\r\nThink about all the time and money being wasted on that, when all you have to say is undergraduate education is free, getting in is going to be the problem because of intellectual standards. Anybody who does an analysis of the money going into universities knows that most of the money comes from the taxpayer anyways.\r\n\r\nSchools exist to create citizens. We live in a democracy. Democracies belong to citizens, not governments or corporations.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Tuition - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','46-revision-9','','','2011-09-08 19:18:15','2011-09-08 19:18:15','',46,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/362',0,'revision','',0),(363,2,'2011-09-08 19:11:03','2011-09-08 19:11:03','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"420\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/ExH2_vbErzg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Tuition - Question','','inherit','open','open','','42-revision-12','','','2011-09-08 19:11:03','2011-09-08 19:11:03','',42,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/363',0,'revision','',0),(364,2,'2011-09-11 14:43:37','2011-09-11 14:43:37','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay about $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have slightly different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats will focus on making tuition more affordable and introducing measures to help with student debt.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-13','','','2011-09-11 14:43:37','2011-09-11 14:43:37','',6,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/364',0,'revision','',0),(365,2,'2011-09-09 15:35:57','2011-09-09 15:35:57','','Wind Turbines - Comment','','inherit','open','open','','160-revision-2','','','2011-09-09 15:35:57','2011-09-09 15:35:57','',160,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/365',0,'revision','',0),(366,2,'2011-09-12 17:52:31','2011-09-12 17:52:31','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/PlSDXsvt7Wc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <iframe width=\"382\" height=\"285\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/XN8izP61_TU\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nI’m John Laforet, and I’m the president of Wind Concerns Ontario.\r\n\r\nI don’t believe the province should be investing more in wind energy, and the reason for that is it’s an expensive, unreliable, and often harmful form of energy production. The Liberals are allowing turbines to be dangerously close to homes, and they generate a lot of noise because they’re about 500 feet tall, they’ve got 8,000 moving parts, and the noise they’re generating makes it very hard for people to sleep in neighbouring homes. What that’s doing is it’s resulting in a whole host of negative health effects.\r\n\r\nOn the economics, wind energy costs four times what power otherwise costs in Ontario. We’re forced to buy it even when we don’t need it, which requires us to subsidize wind developers regardless of supply and demand. What that’s doing is that’s raising everyone’s electricity bills, and we’re wasting a lot of that energy by actually paying neighbouring jurisdictions to take it from us.\r\n\r\nWind power is generated when the wind feels like generating energy, not when we need it. So what that means is we have to build natural gas plants to back up that wind. Those natural gas plants run inefficiently because they’re turned on and off very frequently, depending on what the wind is doing. It’s a very unreasonable way to structure your economy, because it results in more pollution than if you just didn’t have the wind turbines operating.\r\n\r\nWind is still unreliable and will not solve our problems, it’s not going to replace coal because it is so unreliable, so what we need to do is look at solutions to how we’re going to generate clean, affordable, and reliable power.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nMy name is Jutta Splettstoesser, I’m the president of Friends of Wind Ontario.\r\n\r\nYou can see that all around the globe, wind generation is the fastest growing energy generation. I think that speaks for itself. We have to make a plan for the future. We want to go out of coal. By 2014, we want to shut down all the coal plants. What do we use as a substitute? What are our options? One of the options is to substitute it with wind.\r\n\r\nThese are future jobs. There’s many thousands of jobs created, and will be even more created through investment in wind turbines. We need people – qualified people – engineers, builders, electricians, that will have well-paid jobs in the future. For every megawatt of wind that’s produced, it’s about 2,000 liters of water that we preserve.\r\n\r\nThere are no direct health effects proven. There could be indirect health effects, and, just recently, this summer they had the Kent research tribunal, where it was said there could be indirect health effects, but nobody died from a turbine. We will improve technology over the years as well, and you can’t do that in a vacuum. You have to try different things out.\r\n\r\n If you look at the facts, all the benefits that are out there outweigh the complaints of a minority.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Wind Turbines - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','155-revision-7','','','2011-09-12 17:52:31','2011-09-12 17:52:31','',155,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/366',0,'revision','',0),(367,2,'2011-09-12 15:02:18','2011-09-12 15:02:18','<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"420\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/vKT0Ai-hEQ8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','Wind Turbines - Question','','inherit','open','open','','132-revision-4','','','2011-09-12 15:02:18','2011-09-12 15:02:18','',132,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/367',0,'revision','',0),(368,2,'2011-09-12 18:45:00','2011-09-12 18:45:00','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of its principle objectives is to get the province to stop depending on coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing this by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens who don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance – enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators. Another nine wind farms are set to become operational soon. But all of these wind farms only produce a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants that are headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWhile they are about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, wind turbines generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come o