pen','open','','307-revision-14','','','2011-09-15 17:04:55','2011-09-15 17:04:55','',307,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/565',0,'revision','',0),(566,2,'2011-09-15 15:16:12','2011-09-15 15:16:12','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of its principle objectives is to get the province to stop depending on coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing this by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens who don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance – enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators. Another nine wind farms are set to become operational soon. But all of these wind farms only produce a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants that are headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWhile they are about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, wind turbines generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms saying that they\'re eyesores, that they kill local and migratory birds, and that they are often installed without consulting the citizens who are most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ¬– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas. But the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than those posed by wind turbines.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including establishing a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrats and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Wind Turbines','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision-12','','','2011-09-15 15:16:12','2011-09-15 15:16:12','',127,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/566',0,'revision','',0),(567,2,'2011-09-15 14:58:43','2011-09-15 14:58:43','The question of how much students pay to go to university and college comes up every election, and this year, it\'s no different. Here in Ontario, the average university student can expect to pay about $6,300 in tuition each year – and that\'s before the cost of books, accommodations, food, and recreation. That\'s the highest tuition of any province in Canada, and is $800 more than the next most expensive province, New Brunswick. For college students, it\'s a little lower, but they can still expect to pay at least $2,300 a year.\r\n\r\nThe province does run the Ontario Student Assistance Program, or OSAP, to help students cover their costs, and there are always loans available from banks. And, really, there is no denying the value of a degree or a diploma: Seven out of 10 new jobs in Ontario require one or the other. But higher education still leaves students with a heavy debt burden – to the tune of $26,000 – when they graduate, making it as difficult as ever for students and their families to make sure going to school doesn\'t mean going bankrupt.\r\n\r\nElsewhere, such as in the United States of America, students pay a lot more on average to go to university than students here do. But in many European countries, post-secondary education costs are covered, either in part or in full, by the federal government.\r\n\r\nThe three main political parties in Ontario – the New Democratic Party, the Progressive Conservative party, and the Liberal party – have slightly different views of what needs to be changed about post-secondary education. The Liberals say they will reduce tuition costs by a third for families that make less than $160,000. The Progressive Conservatives want to make OSAP available to more families, and to allow 60,000 more students to enrol in post-secondary education. The New Democrats will focus on making tuition more affordable and introducing measures to help with student debt.\r\n\r\nAll of this leads us to ask: Should tuition be free for Ontario students?','Tuition','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision-16','','','2011-09-15 14:58:43','2011-09-15 14:58:43','',6,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/567',0,'revision','',0),(568,2,'2011-09-15 17:20:37','2011-09-15 17:20:37','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of its principle objectives is to get the province to stop depending on coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing this by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens who don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance – enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators. Another nine wind farms are set to become operational soon. But all of these wind farms only produce a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants that are headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWhile they are about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, wind turbines generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms saying that they\'re eyesores, that they kill local and migratory birds, and that they are often installed without consulting the citizens who are most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ¬– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas. But the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than those posed by wind turbines.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including establishing a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrats and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Wind Turbines','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision-13','','','2011-09-15 17:20:37','2011-09-15 17:20:37','',127,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/568',0,'revision','',0),(569,2,'2011-09-15 17:24:18','2011-09-15 17:24:18','<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+Green+Party/LEADERS+-+Mike+Schreiner+answers+Thanasi+Karachotzitis.flv\');\">\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/3GgnJ.jpg\">\n  Green Party\n</div>\n<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEWNEWLIBERAL+RESPONSES/Liberal+Response+6.flv\');\">\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/2jqKw.jpg\">\n  Liberal Party\n</div><div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEWNEWLIBERAL+RESPONSES/Liberal+Response+6.flv\');\">\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/t7IAN.jpg\">\n  Party for People with Special Needs\n</div><div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+Communist/Communist+-+USA.flv\');\">\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/k1LeM.jpg\">\n  Communist Party\n</div><div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+FCP/F