 the years before. Part of the rise is due to more people reporting hate crimes to police in the first place, but crimes against specific minorities also tend to increase when the economy dips.\r\n\r\nOntario, of course, is one of the most diverse jurisdictions on the planet, with people from just about every country and religion on the planet settling here, which makes the need to confront hate crimes all the more pressing. And while hate crimes are still relatively few and far between, their impact on communities – whether it\'s swastikas painted on a synagogue, or a man getting beaten up just because he\'s gay – is often far greater than typical offences.\r\n\r\nDespite their prevalence in Ontario, none of the three major political parties have any specific plans for tackling the rising number of hate crimes in the province. Regardless, authorities on the subject say the key getting rid of hate crimes is to educate the population about the various differences among Ontario\'s many minority groups. Others suggest harsher punishments for those convicted of hate crimes, so as to send a message of deterrence to anyone else who might consider committing one. Another train of thought says hate crimes should be treated the same as any other crime, so as to not glorify the motives of people committing them. Needless to say, there isn\'t a single correct answer on how to combat hate crimes, but it\'s an issue that still needs confronting.','Hate Crimes / Cyber Bullying','','inherit','open','open','','585-revision-2','','','2011-09-18 22:05:02','2011-09-18 22:05:02','',585,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/591',0,'revision','',0),(592,2,'2011-09-15 17:11:19','2011-09-15 17:11:19','<div class=\"leader-answer\" onclick=\"loadMovie(\'https://s3.amazonaws.com/video.election.studentvote.ca/NEW+Green+Party/LEADERS+-+Mike+Schreiner+answers+Jocelyn+DeMone.flv\');\">\r\n  <img src=\"http://i.imgur.com/3GgnJ.jpg\">\r\n  Green Party\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"leader-answer