en','open','','629-revision-4','','','2011-09-20 00:44:55','2011-09-20 00:44:55','',629,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/670',0,'revision','',0),(671,2,'2011-09-19 18:58:35','2011-09-19 18:58:35','The introduction of the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) was among the biggest policy changes that the McGuinty government made. The HST combined the Provincial Sales Tax (PST) and the federal Goods and Services Tax (GST) into one “harmonized” tax of 13 per cent. The HST is meant to streamline the country\'s taxation systems: It rolls the various provincial sales taxes into a common tax that has now been implemented in five provinces. The more efficient the tax system, say some economists, the easier it is for businesses to pass on savings to consumers. But the HST has also added taxes that weren\'t there before, such as on gasoline, electricity, heating, lawyers\' fees, internet subscriptions, and jobs performed by plumbers and electricians.\r\n\r\nWhile there has been a fair bit of criticism in Ontario over the new tax, the reaction here has been nothing compared to that in British Columbia, where former premier Bill Vander Zalm led a petition against the tax, resulting in a vote in which the citizens of B.C. decided to do away with the HST.\r\n\r\nThe HST has been in effect in Ontario since July of 2010. To help families cope with the transition to the new taxation system, the government sent out rebates intended to cover some of the new costs associated with the HST.\r\n\r\nAll three of Ontario\'s major political parties agree that we should keep the HST, but they have different opinions on just what should be affected by the tax. The Liberals stand by their decision to introduce the HST in the first place, and are content with the things that it currently affects. The Progressive Conservatives want to remove the HST from home heating and hydro, and the NDP wants it taken off of gas in addition to heating and hydro. In general, the parties seem to be OK with the tax, then. How about you?','HST','','inherit','open','open','','242-revision-3','','','2011-09-19 18:58:35','2011-09-19 18:58:35','',242,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/671',0,'revision','',0),(672,2,'2011-09-20 00:47:35','2011-09-20 00:47:35','The introduction of the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) was among the biggest policy changes that the McGuinty government made. The HST combined the Provincial Sales Tax (PST) and the federal Goods and Services Tax (GST) into one “harmonized” tax of 13 per cent. The HST is meant to streamline the country\'s taxation systems: It rolls the various provincial sales taxes into a common tax that has now been implemented in five provinces. The more efficient the tax system, say some economists, the easier it is for businesses to pass on savings to consumers. But the HST has also added taxes that weren\'t there before, such as on gasoline, electricity, heating, lawyers\' fees, internet subscriptions, and jobs performed by plumbers and electricians.\r\n\r\nWhile there has been a fair bit of criticism in Ontario over the new tax, the reaction here has been nothing compared to that in British Columbia, where former premier Bill Vander Zalm led a petition against the tax, resulting in a vote in which the citizens of B.C. decided to do away with the HST.\r\n\r\nThe HST has been in effect in Ontario since July of 2010. To help families cope with the transition to the new taxation system, the government sent out rebates intended to cover some of the new costs associated with the HST.\r\n\r\nAll three of Ontario\'s major political parties agree that we should keep the HST, but they have different opinions on just what should be affected by the tax. The Liberals stand by their decision to introduce the HST in the first place, and are content with the things that it currently affects. The Progressive Conservatives want to remove the HST from home heating and hydro, and the NDP wants it taken off of gas in addition to heating and hyd