=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Chris Delaney.mov.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Dwight Duncan.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n[poll id=\"10\"]','HST - Vote','','inherit','open','open','','645-revision-6','','','2011-09-20 00:44:30','2011-09-20 00:44:30','',645,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/676',0,'revision','',0),(677,2,'2011-09-20 00:48:30','2011-09-20 00:48:30','The introduction of the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) was among the biggest policy changes that the McGuinty government made. The HST combined the Provincial Sales Tax (PST) and the federal Goods and Services Tax (GST) into one “harmonized” tax of 13 per cent. The HST is meant to streamline the country\'s taxation systems: It rolls the various provincial sales taxes into a common tax that has now been implemented in five provinces. The more efficient the tax system, say some economists, the easier it is for businesses to pass on savings to consumers. But the HST has also added taxes that weren\'t there before, such as on gasoline, electricity, heating, lawyers\' fees, internet subscriptions, and jobs performed by plumbers and electricians.\r\n\r\nWhile there has been a fair bit of criticism in Ontario over the new tax, the reaction here has been nothing compared to that in British Columbia, where former premier Bill Vander Zalm led a petition against the tax, resulting in a vote in which the citizens of B.C. decided to do away with the HST.\r\n\r\nThe HST has been in effect in Ontario since July of 2010. To help families cope with the transition to the new taxation system, the government sent out rebates intended to cover some of the new costs associated with the HST.\r\n\r\nAll three of Ontario\'s major political parties agree that we should keep the HST, but they have different opinions on just what should be affected by the tax. The Liberals stand by their decision to introduce the HST in the first place, and are content with the things that it currently affects. The Progressive Conservatives want to remove the HST from home heating and hydro, and the NDP wants it taken off of gas in addition to heating and hydro. In general, the parties seem to be OK with the tax, then. How about you?','HST','','inherit','open','open','','242-revision-5','','','2011-09-20 00:48:30','2011-09-20 00:48:30','',242,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/677',0,'revision','',0),(678,2,'2011-09-20 00:34:03','2011-09-20 00:34:03','General crime rates might be dropping across the country, but make no mistake: Hate crimes – in which a person attacks someone else because of his or her race, faith, sexual orientation, gender, or other characteristics – are on the rise. Many cities in Ontario (from major urban centres like Toronto, Ottawa, and London, to smaller communities such as Peterborough and Guelph) reported more hate crimes in 2010 than in the years before. Part of this increase is due to the fact that more people are reporting hate crimes to police than they used to (especially now that more people are aware of what hate crimes are, and how serious they are), but crimes against specific minorities also tend to increase when the economy dips.\r\n\r\nOntario is one of the most diverse regions in the world, with people from just about every country and religion settling here. This makes the need to confront hate crimes in this province all the more pressing. And while hate crimes are still relatively few and far between, their impact on communities – whether it\'s swastikas painted on a synagogue, or a man getting beaten up just because he\'s gay – is often far greater than the impact of typical offences. When hate crimes are committed, the victims (and the religious, gender, ethnic, or other groups that they represent) are made to feel unwelcome, and often live in fear of being targeted for future crimes.\r\n\r\nDespite the rising number of hate crimes in Ontario, none of the three major political parties have any specific plans for tackling the problem. Regardless, some authorities on the subject say the key to getting rid of hate crimes is to educate the population about the differences among Ontario\'s many minority groups, so that those differences are no longer seen as “other.” On the other hand, some people suggest there should be harsher punishments for those convicted of hate crimes, since this could discourage others from committing similar crimes. There is much debate over the best way to address this serious issue, but the evidence is clear: Something must be done. Given what you’ve learned, what do you think is the best way to combat hate crimes in Ontario?','Hate Crimes / Cyber Bullying','','inherit','open','open','','248-revision-8','','','2011-09-20 00:34:03','2011-09-20 00:34:03','',248,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/678',0,'revision','',0),(748,2,'2011-09-15 15:23:36','2011-09-15 15:23:36','Health care is always one of the top issues in any provincial election, and with an aging population and budgets that need balancing, it\'s as pressing an issue as it\'s ever been. One of the key markers of how well our health-care system is run is how long wait times are for emergency-room visits and surgeries. By this measure, Ontario is ahead of the rest of the country. However, wait times vary substantially from region to region within Ontario. This is because wait times largely depend on the number of hospitals, doctors, and other patients needing treatment nearby. There\'s always room for improvement, but how to go about making improvements is often a controversial topic, especially in a country that puts its public health-care system alongside hockey and peace, order, and good government in a list of things that matter most to us.\r\n\r\nThat\'s partly why it\'s so difficult – for politicians, at least – to bring up the idea of establishing more private (as in, for-profit) services as a way to combat wait times. Private health care gives the impression that those who can afford it have an unfair advantage over those who can’t. There is also a sense that it would undermine the public system by stealing resources and doctors. On the other hand, many European countries have a mixture of private and public health care, and access to surgeries and emergency rooms in those countries is substantially better than here in Ontario. Indeed, many in the health-care community blame the monopoly that provincial governments have on health delivery for the inefficiencies that plague the system.\r\n\r\nNone of the three major political parties have brought up private services as a remedy for wait times. The Liberals are running on their record, over the past eight years, of opening hospitals, creating jobs for thousands of nurses, and getting wait times down to the lowest in the country. The New Democratic Party promises to cut wait times in half, while the Progressive Conservatives say they will establish wait-time guarantees that hospital CEOs will be responsible for meeting. The merits of each of these proposals aside, should the province start considering more private delivery of services to help reduce wait times?\r\n','Wait Times','','inherit','open','open','','169-revision-8','','','2011-09-15 15:23:36','2011-09-15 15:23:36','',169,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/748',0,'revision','',0),(679,2,'2011-09-20 00:35:47','2011-09-20 00:35:47','<object width=\"640\" height=\"420\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/6 hate crimes.flv\"},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>','Hate Crimes - The Question','','inherit','open','open','','587-revision-7','','','2011-09-20 00:35:47','2011-09-20 00:35:47','',587,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/679',0,'revision','',0),(680,2,'2011-09-20 10:28:51','2011-09-20 10:28:51','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Karen Mock.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Craig Jones.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\nKaren Mock, Former Chair of the Hate Crimes Community Working Group.\n\nThere need to be very good policies and very good laws in place, but they\'re not worth the paper they\'re written on if they\'re not implemented. Too often people will turn a blind eye, or they won\'t report if they see an incident or if they\'re victimized.\n\nMost of the police services have what they call a hate crimes unit, and it\'s usually connected to what they call the community relations unit. So what they\'re doing is a combination of preventative work - going out into schools and communities - and helping people recognize some of the tell-tale signs.\n\nAnother part of protection is everyone needs to know to whom can they report an incident safely. Not be blamed. \"What did you do to deserve it?\" Protection. Everyone needs protection against bullying, against hate crime, against racism, and all of the other -ism\'s.\n\nNo one agency can or should do it alone. Everybody likes to blame the other, right? So the schoolboard says, \"Well, we would do better if the police would lay more charges.\" And the police say, \"Well we would do better if more people understood how to recognize these tattoos, or report to us to work more effectively.\" So no scapegoating, we need partnerships between the parents, the police, the schools. We\'ve often had times where the schools didn\'t want to bring in the human rights consultant or the community group to work with the students. We have to encourage that there\'s real community partnerships and engagement.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\nLegislation is necessary, but not sufficient. Public education is necessary and sufficient, but it\'s longer-term. Education is about moral regulation, legislation often kicks in after the fact. If you create a hate crime law, it doesn\'t prevent somebody, it doesn\'t deter necessarily, but it does engage after the fact through public denunciation.\n\nThere\'s a temptation in democratic politics to demand responses now. Generally, that\'s not a very effective way to go about things. I think we can draw an important lesson from, and I\'m quite a bit older than you guys, but I remember when impaired driving was \"no big deal.\" \n\nToday, there\'s big stigma around impaired driving. That\'s a process of education. Yes, we have legislation, but again enforcement is variable, sanction is variable, public denunciation doesn\'t seem to have the effect, but public education does. So in democratic societies, you cannot fall into the trap of making the best the enemy of the good. You have to have legislation, but you have to have public education. They have to go together. \n\nI think it has to come from very very strong leadership from the top. When something like a hate crime is committed, our political elites have to be very vocally against that and really make a point of denouncing it.\n\n\n\n  </div>\n</div>','Hate Crimes - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','623-autosave','','','2011-09-20 10:28:51','2011-09-20 10:28:51','',623,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/680',0,'revision','',0),(681,2,'2011-09-20 00:40:21','2011-09-20 00:40:21','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Karen Mock.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Craig Jones.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nVideo transcript 1. Karen Mock.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nVideo transcript 2. Craig Jones.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Hate Crimes - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','623-revision-8','','','2011-09-20 00:40:21','2011-09-20 00:40:21','',623,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/681',0,'revision','',0),(682,2,'2011-09-20 01:43:58','2011-09-20 01:43:58','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Karen Mock.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Craig Jones.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nMy name is Karen Mock.\r\n\r\nThere need to be very good policies and very good laws in place, but they\'re not worth the paper they\'re written on if they\'re not implemented. Too often people will turn a blind eye, or they won\'t report if they see an incident or if they\'re victimized.\r\n\r\nMost of the police services have what they call a hate crimes unit, and it\'s usually connected to what they call the community relations unit. So what they\'re doing is a combination of preventative work - going out into schools and communities - and helping people recognize some of the tell-tale signs.\r\n\r\nAnother part of protection is everyone needs to know to whom can they report an incident safely. Not be blamed. \"What did you do to deserve it?\" Protection. Everyone needs protection against bullying, against hate crime, against racism, and all of the other -ism\'s.\r\n\r\nNo one agency can or should do it alone. Everybody likes to blame the other, right? So the schoolboard says, \"Well, we would do better if the police would lay more charges.\" And the police say, \"Well we would do better if more people understood how to recognize these tattoos, or report to us to work more effectively.\" So no scapegoating, we need partnerships between the parents, the police, the schools. We\'ve often had times where the schools didn\'t want to bring in the human rights consultant or the community group to work with the students. We have to encourage that there\'s real community partnerships and engagement.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nLegislation is necessary, but not sufficient. Public education is necessary and sufficient, but it\'s longer-term. Education is about moral regulation, legislation often kicks in after the fact. If you create a hate crime law, it doesn\'t prevent somebody, it doesn\'t deter necessarily, but it does engage after the fact through public denunciation.\r\n\r\nThere\'s a temptation in democratic politics to demand responses now. Generally, that\'s not a very effective way to go about things. I think we can draw an important lesson from, and I\'m quite a bit older than you guys, but I remember when impaired driving was \"no big deal.\" Today, there\'s big stigma around impaired driving. That\'s a process of education. Yes, we have legislation, but again enforcement is variable, sanction is variable, public denunciation doesn\'t seem to have the effect, but public education does. So in democratic societies, you cannot fall into the trap of making the best the enemy of the good.\r\n\r\nYou have to have legislation, but you have to have public education. They have to go together. I think it has to come from very very strong leadership from the top. When something like a hate crime is committed, our political elites have to be very vocally against that and really make a point of denouncing it.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Hate Crimes - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','623-revision-9','','','2011-09-20 01:43:58','2011-09-20 01:43:58','',623,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/682',0,'revision','',0),(683,2,'2011-09-20 02:07:10','2011-09-20 02:07:10','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Chris Delaney.mov.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Hate Crimes : HST/Dwight Duncan.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\nChris Delaney, lead organizer of Fight HST.\n\nThe HST actually has a very significant impact on people. Particularly low-income people like high school students, like seniors, like the unemployed, middle-income families- they pay the bigger portion of their share of income in taxes through an HST. That applies to everyone, no matter who you are. So if you\'re making $100,000 or $200,000 dollars a year, you pay seven per cent on a cup of coffee at Tim Hortons, and if you\'re making $10,000 a year, you pay seven per cent on a cup of coffee at Tim Hortons. So the guy that\'s not making as much money, it takes a greater portion of his income to support that tax.\n\nGiven that Canada today is a service-based economy, putting a tax on services actually reduces consumption of those services, so it harms the economy.\n\nWell, they say it will create more jobs, it will stimulate the economy. So you might go, \"Okay, well, if that\'s the case I don\'t mind paying a little bit of tax because then I\'ll get a job.\" But everywhere the HST comes in, and everywhere the value added tax comes in, unemployment goes up. It actually is a job killer. Why? Because it reduces consumption.\n\nIf you want to look at economies that are stimulated in Canada right now. The three strongest economies are: Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba. They have unemployment in the five per cent range, they have new economic development going on there, they have one of the lowest per capita debt situations, and lowest cost of living, and there\'s no HST in any one of those three provinces.\n\nThe polls there show 75% of the people there don\'t like it. And yet, here have a political party that, you\'d think it would be a no-brainer to say, \"Get rid of it!\" And they\'ll be elected. But none of them have the guts. And they didn\'t have the guts here either by the way, so the citizens rose up and we revolted. \n  </div>\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\nDwight Duncan, member of Provincial Parliament for Windsor-Tecumseh.\n\nWe created something called a tax plan for jobs and growth where we\'ve actually lowered taxes for 93% of Ontarians, because we cut personal taxes when we did this, we cut the tax rate on the first $37,000 dollars of income when we brought in the HST.\n\nIn the old PST, you couldn\'t see it but there was tax on tax on tax. And so what this does is it unlocks that. So let me give you an example, I often use my watch as an example. On your watch you\'ve got the band, you\'ve got the glass casing, you\'ve got the inner-workings. And each one of those is made separately. If you were a watchmaker, you would pay a provincial sales tax on all of it. What this does, what the HST does, it takes all that tax off and gives it to the business. So the only time you pay the tax is at the end, the consumer.\n\nSince we\'ve implemented the HST, it\'s been a little over a year now, we\'ve seen about 114,000 new jobs. It\'s all part of a tax package, so we cut other taxes, we created a very generous sales tax credit. In fact, students and young people would probably be among the biggest beneficiaries because we cut the tax rate on the first $37,000 dollars of income.\n\nWherever they\'ve implemented a value added tax, which is what the HST is, businesses lower their prices eventually to reflect the fact that they\'re paying less in hidden tax. And so there\'s no debate about that, it happens. \n  </div>\n</div>','HST - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','633-autosave','','','2011-09-20 02:07:10','2011-09-20 02:07:10','',633,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/683',0,'revision','',0),(684,2,'2011-09-20 00:50:17','2011-09-20 00:50:17','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={