pplication/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Transportation/Matti.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Transportation/Tom Laughren.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nMatti Siemiatycki. Professor of Geography and Planning at the University of Toronto.\r\n\r\nThe transportation challenges in these regions are very different. We have gridlock, heavily congested roads throughout many of our urban areas. The cost of congestion to Toronto, a recent study showed, is about three billion dollars a year. So major costs in terms of lost productivity, in terms of wasted fuel, caused by congestion. Very different types of transportation challenges, and the solutions then are very different then in these densely populated urban areas.\r\n\r\nMetrolinx now has a plan, it\'s called \"The Big Move,\" it calls for about $50 billion dollars of investment over the next 25 years. So two billion dollars of investment. It\'s a massive initiative in terms of investing in public transit across the whole region, improving cycling facilities, looking at how we move goods across the region, regional rail and commuter lines. The foundations for these plans are already in place, the question that Metrolinx is now grappling with, and the province more broadly is grappling with is, how do you pay for this?\r\n\r\nNorthern regions and rural areas do get investment from the province as well, so it\'s not an either or, tax dollars are taken from all across the province, and then spread right back out across the province. Investments in major transit initiatives here in Toronto are important to the functioning of the city of Toronto. And one could argue that Toronto is an important economic engine, not just for the city but for the whole province. So investing in transit here in the city is critical.\r\n\r\nPeople may not experience crime every day, they may not experience the health care system every day, and they may not have children or their children might have grown up, and are not in the school system anymore. Those issues may not affect them on a day to day basis. But congestion, every day you step out your door, go to your job, you experience this.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nTom Laughren, Mayor of Timmins.\r\n\r\nWe have huge distances with not a lot of population. So our challenge is being able to put infrastructure in place that can allow our manufacturers, our mines, our forestry companies, to be able to get their product to market at a reasonable price. \r\n\r\nWhen you look at the opportunities from a resource perspective, north of Timmins, when you look at a true East / West route across Northern Ontario to be able to move goods, to move those resources, they need to be definitely putting dollars into rail. And I say that because a lot of what you see in European countries are doing that, as an example. If you\'re really looking to move a lot of bulk, and when you\'re moving resources, you\'re talking about a lot of weight and tonnage. To be globally competitive, rail is the way to go.\r\n\r\nMany of the small airports throughout Northern Ontario, have struggled when it comes to an infrastructure perspective. The ability to be able to get money for their airports, and as well as it is related into very expensive flights if someone\'s trying to go from Timmins to Toronto as an example.\r\n\r\nWe very much lobbied for transportation, improvements to transportation. Again, are we being well received? Are we being listened to? I believe yes. But again, I think you have to look at we have probably 90% of the land masses in northern Ontario, but we have 10% of the population. Factor that into seats sitting in the house, and it\'s an uphill battle for our local MPPs.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Transportation - Debate','','publish','open','open','','transportation-debate','','','2011-09-21 21:14:49','2011-09-21 21:14:49','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=713',0,'post','',0),(714,2,'2011-09-21 19:27:06','2011-09-21 19:27:06','','Transportation - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','713-revision','','','2011-09-21 19:27:06','2011-09-21 19:27:06','',713,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/714',0,'revision','',0),(715,2,'2011-09-21 19:27:18','2011-09-21 19:27:18','<script>\r\nvar idcomments_acct = \'066bba3582108cb66ff7a183c5e6a3b0\';\r\nvar idcomments_post_id;\r\nvar idcomments_post_url;\r\n</script>\r\n<span id=\"IDCommentsPostTitle\" style=\"display:none\"></span>\r\n<script type=\'text/javascript\' src=\'http://www.intensedebate.com/js/genericCommentWrapperV2.js\'></script>','Transportation - Comment','','publish','open','open','','transportation-comment','','','2011-09-21 19:35:04','2011-09-21 19:35:04','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/?p=715',0,'post','',0),(716,2,'2011-09-21 19:27:11','2011-09-21 19:27:11','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','715-revision','','','2011