//election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/737',0,'revision','',0),(738,2,'2011-09-15 17:21:54','2011-09-15 17:21:54','The Green Energy Act was one of the hallmarks of Dalton McGuinty\'s last term as premier, and one of its principle objectives is to get the province to stop depending on coal power by 2014. The Liberals plan on doing this by shifting a lot of the province\'s power supply to wind farms, but that\'s run into a lot of opposition from citizens who don\'t want turbines in their communities. Since 2006, 13 wind farms have sprung up across the province, generating 1,300 megawatts at peak performance – enough to power about 2.5 million refrigerators. Another nine wind farms are set to become operational soon. But all of these wind farms only produce a fraction of the more than 4,000 megawatts generated by the coal power plants that are headed for closure.\r\n\r\nWhile they are about as harmless to the environment as power plants can be, wind turbines generate energy inconsistently because they are dependent on wind speed. Rural communities have also come out against the farms saying that they\'re eyesores, that they kill local and migratory birds, and that they are often installed without consulting the citizens who are most affected by them. There are also many more efficient ¬– essentially meaning cheaper – ways of producing electricity, such as hydro, nuclear power, and natural gas. But the environmental risks posed by those last two are substantially higher than those posed by wind turbines.\r\n\r\nThe Liberals plan on following through with their Green Energy Act, including establishing a “feed-in tariff” that pays people who erect their own wind turbines or solar panels and connect them to the power grid. Both the New Democrats and the Progressive Conservatives say they will give more power to towns, cities, and counties to decide whether they want wind farms in their backyards, although all three parties support the expansion of renewable energy sources throughout the province. The question is, then, should the province be investing so heavily in wind power?','Wind Turbines','','inherit','open','open','','127-revision-14','','','2011-09-15 17:21:54','2011-09-15 17:21:54','',127,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/738',0,'revision','',0),(739,2,'2011-09-21 21:17:00','2011-09-21 21:17:00','Transportation, whether its gridlock in Toronto, public transit in Ottawa, or the quality of roads in the North, is an issue that affects each and every person in Ontario. And with the province\'s population growing every day, its transit needs aren\'t about to get any easier in the coming years. Toronto, for example, has the longest commute times of anywhere in the country, and the worst gridlock in the continent. Finding ways to ease congestion will not only make the region more liveable, but will help the country\'s economic heartland continue to grow well into this century. Public transit certainly plays a part in that future, but just who pays for it – users, the city, the province, the federal government, or a mixture of all of them – remains up for debate.\r\n\r\nIn northern Ontario, there are billions of dollars in minerals just waiting to be mined, but there aren\'t enough roads to get those minerals out of there. Developing proper infrastructure in the more remote parts of the province could help tap the economic potential of those traditionally disadvantaged – and heavy aboriginal – areas for the benefit of the entire province. Saying one thing and actually making it happen are two very different matters, and more often than not, the sparsely populated North gets overlooked in favour of vote-rich southern Ontario.\r\n\r\nThe three major political parties all have differing plans on how to cope with transit issues, but they all tend to focus on the Greater Toronto Area, or GTA. The New Democratic Party, for example, want to freeze the price of transit fares in exchange for sharing the cost of public transportat