 data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Youth Employment/Matt Wood.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nLauren Friese transcript.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nMatt Wood transcript.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Youth Employment - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','755-revision-4','','','2011-09-23 16:08:18','2011-09-23 16:08:18','',755,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/766',0,'revision','',0),(767,2,'2011-09-23 16:05:03','2011-09-23 16:05:03','Fifteen per cent of youth between the ages of 15 and 25 in Ontario are unemployed. This number is twice as high as the unemployment rate for the province as a whole, and has grown considerably since the recession of 2008-09. Making matters worse is the rising price of tuition for college and university programs, as many students must take on staggering levels of debt to pay for their education without a steady income to help them out. And many of the jobs that youth do end up in are in low-skill, low-wage fields such as hospitality or retail. Imagine you\'re well into your 20s: You have a degree or a diploma, but, as a result of the high costs of education, you are tens of thousands of dollars in debt, and you can\'t find a job that puts your skills to use. In this scenario, it\'s easy to become dispirited.\r\n\r\nBut youth unemployment, or underemployment, doesn\'t just affect those without jobs. If university graduates can\'t find jobs, there\'s a good chance they\'ll end up living at home, putting additional financial strain on their parents. Furthermore, the economy is missing out on the one time of people’s lives when they can fully devote themselves to their careers before having to worry about family, home ownership, or other such changes that come about later in life. And letting the career-specific skills youth develop in college or university go to waste as they work menial jobs means they might never live up to their full potential.\r\n\r\nCreating jobs is a hot topic in this election. The Progressive Conservatives want to create 200,000 new apprenticeship positions over the next four years, while the New Democratic Party says it will offer tax credits to any employer that creates a new full-time position. The Liberals have announced a similar measure to get employers to hire immigrants, and are running on their record of restoring more jobs to the province than were lost during the recession. While creating jobs has been one of the most dominant themes of the election campaign so far, the three main political parties don\'t offer a whole lot in the way of addressing youth unemployment specifically. What role should the government play in getting the youth-unemployment rate down, and what\'s the best way to do so?','Youth Employment','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision-4','','','2011-09-23 16:05:03','2011-09-23 16:05:03','',237,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/767',0,'revision','',0),(768,2,'2011-09-23 16:06:07','2011-09-23 16:06:07','<object width=\"640\" height=\"420\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Youth Employment/8_youth employment.mov.flv\"},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>','Youth Employment - Question','','inherit','open','open','','752-revision-3','','','2011-09-23 16:06:07','2011-09-23 16:06:07','',752,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/768',0,'revision','',0),(769,2,'2011-09-23 17:00:50','2011-09-23 17:00:50','<div id=\"debate-arena-holder\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Youth Employment/Laura Friese.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n   <object width=\"382\" height=\"285\" id=\"s3EmbedVideo\" name=\"s3EmbedVideo\" data=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://releases.flowplayer.org/swf/flowplayer-3.2.7.swf\" /><param name=\"allowfullscreen\" value=\"true\" /><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"flashvars\" value=\'config={\"clip\":{\"url\":\"http://video.election.studentvote.ca.s3.amazonaws.com/Youth Employment/Matt Wood.flv\", \"autoPlay\":false},\"canvas\":{\"backgroundColor\":\"#112233\"}}}\' /></object>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"debate-arena-text\">\r\n  <div class=\"position-one\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">Against</div>\r\nLauren Friese, founder, TalentEgg.ca.\r\n\r\nYouth unemployment is particularly high because there\'s a mismatch in terms of what employers are looking for and what Canada\'s youth are able to provide to the workplace.\r\n\r\nYou don\'t really hear about students from Waterloo\'s engineering department being unemployed, in fact I would guess the unemployment rate there is close to zero. And then there\'s all these other people who are studying arts and science, or even business, or even engineering in schools that are as not well-known, that just can\'t get a job. I think that there\'s just a mismatch in terms of the programs and the skillsets that employers hire from, and what students are offering.\r\n\r\nWe would see a major shift, or change in youth unemployment and underemployment numbers, if employers started to train in-house, to re-train students that have perhaps studied history to be in marketing. This isn\'t a crazy idea, this is something that is already being done in other countries.\r\n\r\nI think on the flip side, students need to make it easier for employers to take those kinds of chances on them. Students and recent graduates need to understand that when an employer hires someone that not only did not take business, or engineering or technology or whatever it may be, but also has absolutely no work experience, no workplace polish- that is a huge risk on the part of the employer. I would say students should stay in your history programs, but on the side get relevant experience. Make sure that you can present yourself properly in an interview. Learn how to dress for success, that type of thing.\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div class=\"position-two\">\r\n    <div class=\"title\">For</div>\r\nMatt Wood, executive director, First Work, Ontario Association of Youth Employment Centres.\r\n\r\nYoung people could go in anytime that was convenient for them. There would be a computer lab they could have access to, they would get resume advice, and they could take workshops on all sorts of job-hunting tips and techniques. Nowadays in Ontario, they\'re taking an all-ages approach. So all ages of folks are welcome to drop into Ontario centres, and there are more of those centres around then there used to be. What we\'re finding is that while youth can stil get many of the same services that they used to get, and are still quite satisfied and having good experiences, a lot of young people aren\'t taking advantage of the services as much as they used to.  You have a room full of 40-year-old folks who are job-searching after they may have been laid off. It\'s just a different experience, and young people may not feel as comfortable going into that atmosphere.\r\n\r\nYouth employment services would have to achieve much greater scale than it has now, in order to guarantee a job for every young person. If we\'re going to be influencing such a large thing as the Ontario economy, you have to be a very large service. Right now, in the midst of posterity and cutbacks, you\'re not going to see that kind of investment. We\'d like to see about six million dollars found to support greater youth outreach in the current employment services. It\'s a very small number in the big scheme of things. But we feel that would provide the kind of support that many centres need to make the extra effort that young people need, to find them, to encourage them to come in, to have youth-friendly focused workshops, and other employment support for them.\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>','Youth Employment - Debate','','inherit','open','open','','755-revision-5','','','2011-09-23 17:00:50','2011-09-23 17:00:50','',755,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/769',0,'revision','',0),(770,2,'2011-09-23 16:11:07','2011-09-23 16:11:07','<script>\r\nvar idcomments_acct = \'066bba3582108cb66ff7a183c5e6a3b0\';\r\nvar idcomments_post_id;\r\nvar idcomments_post_url;\r\n</script>\r\n<span id=\"IDCommentsPostTitle\" style=\"display:none\"></span>\r\n<script type=\'text/javascript\' src=\'http://www.intensedebate.com/js/genericCommentWrapperV2.js\'></script>