','','235-revision-5','','','2011-09-23 19:37:02','2011-09-23 19:37:02','',235,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/798',0,'revision','',0),(799,2,'2011-09-23 20:10:46','2011-09-23 20:10:46','One in four students in Canada is considered overweight, and that number is expected to rise in the coming years. Unbalanced diets and inactive lifestyles are a big part of the reason Canada\'s getting fat, and they pose long-term threats to Ontario\'s health-care system. Overweight and obese people are more likely to develop heart disease, diabetes, depression, and a raft of other issues than those with healthier body weights. As if a rapidly aging population wasn\'t straining the health-care system enough, the looming obesity crisis only stands to complicate matters.\r\n\r\nFinding a way to curb the growth of Ontarians\' waistlines is a tricky proposition. The government can\'t simply tell people what they should and shouldn\'t eat. However, there are ways to encourage citizens to lead healthier lifestyles. One proposal is that all students should be required to take gym classes throughout their entire school career, as getting young people to develop healthy habits such as exercising is seen as one of the best ways to help them ward off obesity for the rest of their lives. Other suggestions include posting the calorie counts of meals on restaurant menus, banning junk food in schools, and making healthier foods – especially fruits and vegetables – more affordable for more people.\r\n\r\nSo far in this election, the New Democratic Party has proposed introducing mandatory gym class, forcing chain restaurants to display their food’s nutritional information, and banning junk-food advertisements aimed at kids. The Liberals want to launch a “Council on Childhood Obesity” that would aim to bring obesity levels in children down by 20 per cent, while the Progressive Conservatives haven\'t touched the issue yet. What do you think: Would measures like mandatory gym class help the province get in shape?','Obesity / Health','','inherit','open','open','','235-revision-6','','','2011-09-23 20:10:46','2011-09-23 20:10:46','',235,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/799',0,'revision','',0),(800,2,'2011-09-23 17:27:38','2011-09-23 17:27:38','Fifteen per cent of youth between the ages of 15 and 25 in Ontario are unemployed. This number is twice as high as the unemployment rate for the province as a whole, and has grown considerably since the recession of 2008-09. Making matters worse is the rising price of tuition for college and university programs, as many students must take on staggering levels of debt to pay for their education without a steady income to help them out. And many of the jobs that youth do end up in are in low-skill, low-wage fields such as hospitality or retail. Imagine you\'re well into your 20s: You have a degree or a diploma, but, as a result of the high costs of education, you are tens of thousands of dollars in debt, and you can\'t find a job that puts your skills to use. In this scenario, it\'s easy to become dispirited.\r\n\r\nBut youth unemployment, or underemployment, doesn\'t just affect those without jobs. If university graduates can\'t find jobs, there\'s a good chance they\'ll end up living at home, putting additional financial strain on their parents. Furthermore, the economy is missing out on the one time of people’s lives when they can fully devote themselves to their careers before having to worry about family, home ownership, or other such changes that come about later in life. And letting the career-specific skills youth develop in college or university go to waste as they work menial jobs means they might never live up to their full potential.\r\n\r\nCreating jobs is a hot topic in this election. The Progressive Conservatives want to create 200,000 new apprenticeship positions over the next four years, while the New Democratic Party says it will offer tax credits to any employer that creates a new full-time position. The Liberals have announced a similar measure to get employers to hire immigrants, and are running on their record of restoring more jobs to the province than were lost during the recession. While creating jobs has been one of the most dominant themes of the election campaign so far, the three main political parties don\'t offer a whole lot in the way of addressing youth unemployment specifically. What role should the government play in getting the youth-unemployment rate down, and what\'s the best way to do so?','Youth Employment','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision-6','','','2011-09-23 17:27:38','2011-09-23 17:27:38','',237,'http://election.studentvote.ca/uncategorized/800',0,'revision','',0),(801,2,'2011-09-23 20:38:05','2011-09-23 20:38:05','','SV_Header_HST','','inherit','open','open','','sv_header','','','2011-09-23 20:38:05','2011-09-23 20:38:05','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(802,2,'2011-09-23 20:38:36','2011-09-23 20:38:36','','SV_Header_YouthEmployment','','inherit','open','open','','sv_header_youthemployment','','','2011-09-23 20:38:36','2011-09-23 20:38:36','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_YouthEmployment.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(803,2,'2011-09-23 20:39:05','2011-09-23 20:39:05','','SV_Header_Transportation','','inherit','open','open','','sv_header_transportation','','','2011-09-23 20:39:05','2011-09-23 20:39:05','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Transportation.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(804,2,'2011-09-23 20:39:26','2011-09-23 20:39:26','','SV_Header_Obesity','','inherit','open','open','','sv_header_obesity','','','2011-09-23 20:39:26','2011-09-23 20:39:26','',0,'http://election.studentvote.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/SV_Header_Obesity.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(805,2,'2011-09-23 18:40:57','2011-09-23 18:40:57','<div style=\"width:100%;